SSRIs?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increases serotonin synthesis","Inhibits noradrenaline reuptake","Inhibits monoamine oxidase enzyme","Inhibits the presynaptic serotonin transporter protein","Antagonises serotonin receptors"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of action of SSRIs involves the \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibition of serotonin transporter protein on presynaptic neurons\u003C/strong\u003E. This prevents serotonin from being taken back up into the presynaptic terminal, increasing serotonin levels within the synaptic cleft.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases serotonin synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E - SSRIs do not directly affect serotonin production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits noradrenaline reuptake\u003C/strong\u003E - SSRIs are selective for serotonin and do not significantly affect noradrenaline.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits monoamine oxidase enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the mechanism of monoamine oxidase inhibitors, not SSRIs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntagonises serotonin receptors\u003C/strong\u003E - This would decrease rather than enhance serotonergic neurotransmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe elevated synaptic serotonin concentration produces enhanced serotonergic signalling, which is believed to explain the therapeutic benefit of their use in treating depressive disorders.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors work by blocking the serotonin transporter protein in presynaptic neurons, which increases serotonin concentration in the synaptic cleft.","Selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) do not directly affect other neurotransmitter systems like noradrenaline or dopamine.","The therapeutic effects of SSRIs are due to increased serotonergic neurotransmission in the synaptic cleft."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92504"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14723"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92504"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-29T10:55:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-29T10:55:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7416"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110233"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","